Problem Statement¶

Context¶

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data scientist at AllLife bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective¶

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customer’s age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)? (0: No, 1: Yes)

Exploratory Data Analysis.¶

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Questions:

  1. What is the distribution of mortgage attribute? Are there any noticeable patterns or outliers in the distribution?
  2. How many customers have credit cards?
  3. What are the attributes that have a strong correlation with the target attribute (personal loan)?
  4. How does a customer's interest in purchasing a loan vary with their age?
  5. How does a customer's interest in purchasing a loan vary with their education?

Answers:

The mortgage distribution is right-skewed, meaning most customers have relatively low mortgage amounts, while a small group has significantly higher values. There are several outliers, which suggests that a few customers have much larger mortgages compared to the majority.

When looking at patterns and outliers, we can see that outliers exist in multiple attributes, especially mortgage and income. Another issue is that the experience attribute contains negative values, which doesn’t make sense and should be corrected. Additionally, credit card spending (CCAvg) is highly skewed, with a few customers spending much more than the rest.

Regarding credit card ownership, the dataset includes a CreditCard attribute that indicates whether a customer has a card. A large portion of customers do own a credit card, though the exact percentage isn't explicitly mentioned.

As for the factors that influence personal loan approvals, some key attributes stand out:

  • Income – Higher-income individuals are more likely to take a personal loan.

  • Credit Card Spending (CCAvg) – Customers who spend more on credit cards tend to accept loans more often.

  • Education Level – Those with higher education levels (graduate or advanced degrees) show a greater tendency to take loans.

  • CD Account Ownership – Customers who have Certificate of Deposit (CD) accounts are more likely to accept loan offers.

When we analyze age and education in relation to loan interest, there's no strong correlation between age and loan acceptance. However, middle-aged customers (30-50 years old) seem to be more inclined to take loans compared to younger or older individuals. On the education front, graduates and those with advanced degrees are far more likely to accept personal loans than those with only an undergraduate education.

Outlier Detection and Treatment (if needed)

In [173]:
# Select only numerical columns for quantile calculation
numerical_data = data.select_dtypes(include=['float64', 'int64'])

# Calculate Q1 (25th percentile) and Q3 (75th percentile) for numerical columns
Q1 = numerical_data.quantile(0.25)
Q3 = numerical_data.quantile(0.75)

# Calculate the IQR
IQR = Q3 - Q1

# Define lower and upper bounds for outliers
lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

# Find the outliers in the numerical columns
outliers_condition = (numerical_data < lower_bound) | (numerical_data > upper_bound)

# Calculate the percentage of outliers in the dataset
outlier_percentage = outliers_condition.sum() / len(data) * 100

# Print the percentage of outliers
print(outlier_percentage)

Model Building¶

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

Model Evaluation Criteria:

The model can make two types of wrong predictions:

False Positive (FP): Predicting that a person will buy a loan when they actually don't.

Impact: This results in wasted resources, such as marketing or sales efforts directed at customers who are not interested, potentially reducing the campaign’s efficiency.

False Negative (FN): Predicting that a person will not buy a loan, but they actually do.

Impact: This leads to a loss of opportunity, as the marketing and sales team fail to engage with potential customers who could have become buyers, undermining the campaign's success.

Model Building¶

Model Performance Evaluation: Scoring and Confusion Matrix

In [26]:
def evaluate_classification_model(model, X, y):
    """
    Function to evaluate the performance of a classification model using various metrics.

    Parameters:
    - model: Trained classifier model
    - X: Independent variables (features)
    - y: True labels (target variable)

    Returns:
    - A DataFrame containing the evaluation metrics (Accuracy, Recall, Precision, F1).
    """
    # Make predictions using the provided model
    y_pred = model.predict(X)

    # Calculate performance metrics
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y, y_pred)      # Accuracy metric
    recall = recall_score(y, y_pred)          # Recall metric
    precision = precision_score(y, y_pred)   # Precision metric
    f1 = f1_score(y, y_pred)                  # F1-score metric

    # Create a DataFrame to store the metrics
    metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(
        {"Accuracy": [accuracy], "Recall": [recall], "Precision": [precision], "F1": [f1]}
    )

    return metrics_df
In [25]:
def make_confusion_matrix(model, X, y, ax=None):
    """
    Function to plot the confusion matrix with percentages.

    Parameters:
    - model: Trained classifier model
    - X: Independent variables (features)
    - y: True labels (target variable)
    - ax: Matplotlib axis (optional, default is None)

    If 'ax' is provided, the plot will be drawn on the given axis.
    Otherwise, a new axis will be created.
    """
    # Predict the target variable using the model
    y_pred = model.predict(X)

    # Generate the confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y, y_pred)

    # Prepare labels with percentages for display
    labels = np.asarray(
        [["{0:0.0f}\n{1:.2%}".format(item, item / cm.sum())] for item in cm.flatten()]
    ).reshape(cm.shape)

    # If no axis is provided, create a new one
    if ax is None:
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 4))

    # Create the heatmap using seaborn
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=labels, fmt="", cmap="Blues", ax=ax, cbar=False)

    # Set axis labels and title
    ax.set_ylabel("True Label")
    ax.set_xlabel("Predicted Label")
    ax.set_title("Confusion Matrix")

Pre-pruning is applied using hyperparameters like max_depth, min_samples_split, and min_samples_leaf to prevent overfitting.

Post-Pruning (Cost Complexity Pruning)

Post-pruning is done by pruning the tree based on cost-complexity pruning (ccp_alpha), which controls complexity by penalizing leaf nodes with little gain.

In [109]:
path = best_pre_pruned.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)
ccp_alphas, impurities = path.ccp_alphas, path.impurities

# Train multiple trees with different ccp_alpha values
pruned_models = []
train_scores = []
test_scores = []

for alpha in ccp_alphas[:-1]:  # Exclude last alpha that prunes the entire tree
    pruned_tree = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42, ccp_alpha=alpha)
    pruned_tree.fit(X_train, y_train)
    pruned_models.append(pruned_tree)

    # Store performance metrics
    train_scores.append(pruned_tree.score(X_train, y_train))
    test_scores.append(pruned_tree.score(X_test, y_test))

# Plot pruning effect
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
plt.plot(ccp_alphas[:-1], train_scores, label="Train Accuracy", marker='o')
plt.plot(ccp_alphas[:-1], test_scores, label="Test Accuracy", marker='o')
plt.xlabel("ccp_alpha")
plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
plt.legend()
plt.title("Effect of Cost-Complexity Pruning on Model Performance")
plt.show()

# Train the final pruned model
final_model = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42, ccp_alpha=best_ccp_alpha)
final_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

In [145]:
# Calculate recall for training and testing sets using pruned models
recall_train_set = []
recall_test_set = []

for clf in pruned_models:
    pred_train = clf.predict(X_train)
    pred_test = clf.predict(X_test)

    recall_train_set.append(recall_score(y_train, pred_train))
    recall_test_set.append(recall_score(y_test, pred_test))

# Adjusted ccp_alphas to match the models used (exclude the last ccp_alpha)
ccp_alphas_adjusted = ccp_alphas[:-1]

# Ensure consistent lengths
assert len(ccp_alphas_adjusted) == len(recall_train_set) == len(recall_test_set), \
    f"Mismatch in lengths: {len(ccp_alphas_adjusted)}, {len(recall_train_set)}, {len(recall_test_set)}"

# Plot Recall vs alpha for training and testing sets
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 5))
ax.set_xlabel("ccp_alpha")
ax.set_ylabel("Recall")
ax.set_title("Recall vs ccp_alpha for Training and Testing Sets")
ax.plot(ccp_alphas_adjusted, recall_train_set, marker="o", label="Train Recall", drawstyle="steps-post")
ax.plot(ccp_alphas_adjusted, recall_test_set, marker="o", label="Test Recall", drawstyle="steps-post")
ax.legend()
plt.show()

# Select the best model based on recall while preventing overfitting
best_model_index = np.argmax(recall_test_set)  # Chooses the highest test recall
best_ccp_alpha = ccp_alphas_adjusted[best_model_index]

# Print the best ccp_alpha
print(f"Best model found with ccp_alpha = {best_ccp_alpha}")


# Ensure test recall is high while avoiding a large gap from training recall
gap_threshold = 0.05
for i, alpha in enumerate(ccp_alphas_adjusted):
    if abs(recall_train_set[i] - recall_test_set[i]) <= gap_threshold:
        best_ccp_alpha = alpha
        best_model_index = i
        break  # Stop at the first acceptable model

# Train the final selected model
final_model = DecisionTreeClassifier(ccp_alpha=best_ccp_alpha, random_state=1)
final_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

  • Implemented using hyperparameters like max_depth, min_samples_split, and

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

Key Insights

Income is the Most Influential Factor

  • Higher-income customers are more likely to accept personal loans.

  • Customers with an annual income above a certain threshold have a significantly higher likelihood of purchasing loans.

Family Size and Education Matter

  • Customers with larger families (3 or more members) show a higher tendency to take personal loans.

  • Highly educated customers (Graduate & Advanced degrees) are more inclined to take loans compared to undergraduates.

Credit Card Spending is a Strong Indicator

  • Customers with higher credit card spending (CCAvg) tend to accept personal loans more often.

  • The average monthly spending threshold can be a key marketing segmentation metric.

Existing Banking Relationships Play a Role

  • Customers with Certificate of Deposit (CD) accounts are more likely to take personal loans.

  • Those with Securities Accounts show lower interest in personal loans.

Online Banking Users Show Higher Engagement

  • Customers using online banking services are more responsive to loan offerings.

Business Recommendations

Target High-Income Customers with Personalized Offers

  • Focus marketing efforts on customers earning above the identified income threshold.

  • Offer them exclusive loan products with personalized interest rates.

Create Family-Based Loan Offers

  • Design loan products with family-friendly incentives (e.g., lower interest rates for customers with 3+ family members).

  • Run promotional campaigns targeting middle-aged customers with families.

Leverage Credit Card Spending Data for Loan Marketing

  • Identify customers with higher monthly credit card spending and target them for personal loan offers.

  • Offer credit card-linked personal loans with better terms.

Promote Loan Offers to Online Banking Users

  • Online banking users are more engaged—run digital campaigns and in-app notifications.

  • Provide instant pre-approved loan offers through the bank’s online platform.

Upsell to Certificate of Deposit (CD) Account Holders

  • Since CD account holders are more likely to take loans, create CD-backed personal loans with lower interest rates.

  • Market personal loans as a wealth management strategy for CD customers.
